  "local_port": 41720,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some cool Java tricks?",
  "response": "Java is a versatile and powerful programming language, and there are many \"cool tricks\" and techniques that can make your code more efficient, readable, or elegant. Here are some fun and useful Java tricks:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Use `var` for Local Variable Type Inference (Java 10+)**\nJava 10 introduced `var` for local variable type inference, making your code cleaner.\n```java\nvar list = new ArrayList<String>();\nvar map = new HashMap<Integer, String>();\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Swap Two Numbers Without a Temporary Variable**\nYou can swap two numbers without using a temporary variable.\n```java\nint a = 5;\nint b = 10;\na = a + b; // a = 15\nb = a - b; // b = 5\na = a - b; // a = 10\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Use `String.format()` for Clean String Formatting**\n`String.format()` is a neat way to format strings, similar to `printf`.\n```java\nString name = \"Alice\";\nint age = 25;\nString message = String.format(\"Hello, %s! You are %d years old.\", name, age);\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Use `Collections.singletonList()` for Single-Element Lists**\nIf you need a list with a single element, use `Collections.singletonList()` to create an immutable list.\n```java\nList<String> list = Collections.singletonList(\"Hello\");\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Use `Optional` to Avoid Null Checks**\n`Optional` can help you avoid `NullPointerException` and make your code more expressive.\n```java\nOptional<String> name = Optional.ofNullable(getName());\nString result = name.orElse(\"Default\");\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Use `Streams` for Functional-Style Programming**\nJava 8 introduced Streams, which allow you to process collections in a functional style.\n```java\nList<String> names = List.of(\"Alice\", \"Bob\", \"Charlie\");\nList<String> filtered = names.stream()\n                             .filter(n -> n.startsWith(\"A\"))\n                             .toList();\n```\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Use `Math.min()` and `Math.max()` for Simple Comparisons**\nThese methods are great for avoiding verbose if-else statements.\n```java\nint min = Math.min(a, b);\nint max = Math.max(a, b);\n```\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Use `switch` Expressions (Java 12+)**\nJava 12 introduced `switch` expressions, which are more concise and powerful.\n```java\nString day = \"Monday\";\nString type = switch (day) {\n    case \"Monday\", \"Tuesday\" -> \"Weekday\";\n    case \"Saturday\", \"Sunday\" -> \"Weekend\";\n    default -> \"Unknown\";\n};\n```\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Use `Objects.requireNonNull()` for Null Checks**\nThis method ensures a non-null value and throws `NullPointerException` if the value is null.\n```java\npublic void setName(String name) {\n    this.name = Objects.requireNonNull(name, \"Name cannot be null\");\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 10. **Use `ThreadLocalRandom` for Random Numbers**\n`ThreadLocalRandom` is more efficient than `Random` for generating random numbers in multithreaded environments.\n```java\nint random = ThreadLocalRandom.current().nextInt(1, 100);\n```\n\n---\n\n### 11. **Use `try-with-resources` for Automatic Resource Management**\nThis ensures that resources like files or streams are closed automatically.\n```java\ntry (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(\"file.txt\"))) {\n    String line;\n    while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {\n        System.out.println(line);\n    }\n} catch (IOException e) {\n    e.printStackTrace();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 12. **Use `Bitwise Operators` for Efficient Calculations**\nBitwise operators can be used for quick calculations, like checking if a number is even or odd.\n```java\nboolean isEven = (number & 1) == 0;\n```\n\n---\n\n### 13. **Use `Record` for Immutable Data Classes (Java 14+)**\n`Record` automatically generates getters, `equals()`, `hashCode()`, and `toString()` methods.\n```java\nrecord Person(String name, int age) {}\nPerson person = new Person(\"Alice\", 25);\nSystem.out.println(person.name()); // Alice\n```\n\n---\n\n### 14. **Use `Pattern Matching for `instanceof` (Java 16+)**\nSimplify type checks and casting with pattern matching.\n```java\nif (obj instanceof String s) {\n    System.out.println(s.toUpperCase());\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 15. **Use `Text Blocks` for Multiline Strings (Java 13+)**\nText blocks make it easy to work with multiline strings.\n```java\nString json = \"\"\"\n    {\n        \"name\": \"Alice\",\n        \"age\": 25\n    }\n    \"\"\";\n```\n\n---\n\nThese tricks can help you write cleaner, more efficient, and modern Java code. Experiment with them to see how they can enhance your programming workflow!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
